threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a MIPS variant of the Mozi P2P botnet. The binary propagates by exploiting multiple known command injection vulnerabilities in IoT devices, as evidenced by numerous HTTP request strings targeting web interfaces (e.g., `GET /boaform/admin/formPing?...wget ...`), HNAP, and GPON services. It downloads and executes payloads with names like `Mozi.m` and `Mozi.a`. The malware establishes persistence by writing to startup scripts such as `/etc/rc.local` and `/etc/init.d/S95baby.sh`, and attempts to remount filesystems as read-write. It uses a DHT-based P2P network for command and control, indicated by tags like `[/cnc]` and its complex network initialization routines.
